00:00:33.279 --> 00:00:38.959
And when you see a patient that has cancer, a common type, of course, is solid tumors. They

00:00:38.959 --> 00:00:42.480
may have bladder cancer, they may have liver cancer, they may have lung cancer, and so on.

00:00:43.439 --> 00:00:48.880
And of course, a common worry about that is it's going to metastasize. And of course,

00:00:48.880 --> 00:00:52.639
that causes a lot of pain for a patient as well. It's all cancers are pretty terrible.

00:00:53.279 --> 00:00:56.560
But there's another kind of cancer called blood cancer. And that's what we're going to focus on

00:00:56.560 --> 00:01:01.520
today in this slide. And that's already all over your body. Anywhere there's blood in your body,

00:01:01.520 --> 00:01:08.239
there are going to be cells and some particular types of blood cancers are lymphoma. Another

00:01:08.239 --> 00:01:13.360
kind is multiple myeloma, which is the product that I work on treats. And the way this works,

00:01:13.360 --> 00:01:18.160
as far as treatment goes now, is the blood is taken from the patient first.

00:01:19.040 --> 00:01:23.279
And then the T cells are harvested out of that. So that's a there's a lot of complicated steps

00:01:23.279 --> 00:01:26.879
to this process, even though it may look complicated itself, there's a lot more going on.

00:01:27.599 --> 00:01:33.599
And what happens after those T cells are taken out is just some amazing engineering goes on.

00:01:33.599 --> 00:01:38.720
We take those T cells, or the engineers and scientists that work on this and manufacturing

00:01:38.720 --> 00:01:42.639
take these T cells, and they supercharge them. And of course, T cells come from your thymus.

00:01:43.279 --> 00:01:48.959
They are your protection against all sorts of things, infections, cancers, and so on. And they

00:01:48.959 --> 00:01:54.239
are working constantly. And they are produced by the millions every day in your body. And we're

00:01:54.239 --> 00:02:00.160
very fortunate to have them for a healthy immune system. The acronym there for GMP is good

00:02:00.160 --> 00:02:05.839
manufacturing process or practice. We won't talk very much about that except to say,

00:02:06.959 --> 00:02:12.639
when we have those T cells taken out of a diseased patient's body, we want to give some

00:02:12.639 --> 00:02:18.160
genetic instructions to them. And those genetic instructions will help in supercharging those

00:02:18.160 --> 00:02:23.039
already very capable and armed force types of T cells to help protect and attack the cancer. So

00:02:23.039 --> 00:02:28.880
they're very specific. With the instructions, you can make these T cells grow what's called chimeric

00:02:28.880 --> 00:02:37.279
antigen receptors or CAR T. So type of T cell, type of white blood cell. And they will find those

00:02:37.279 --> 00:02:41.919
multiple myeloma cells that are coursing through your blood, and they will bind to them and they

00:02:41.919 --> 00:02:46.800
will attack them and destroy them. And the hope with this kind of treatment now, a platform that's

00:02:46.800 --> 00:02:51.759
been emerging now for about the past 10 years or so, the research goes way behind that, is that it

00:02:51.759 --> 00:02:57.440
will only have to be given one time. And for multiple myeloma patients, when this product that

00:02:57.440 --> 00:03:02.800
I work on got first approved, it was what's called a fourth line therapy. So that means they've tried

00:03:02.800 --> 00:03:06.800
other things. And other things may be very successful for months, for years. There's been

00:03:06.800 --> 00:03:13.839
incredible since, say, the 1970s, you know, doubling in years in terms of survival. But

00:03:13.839 --> 00:03:18.320
ultimately, you can't get rid of multiple myeloma. We don't want to use the word cure because that

00:03:18.320 --> 00:03:22.479
would imply that it will never come back again. In some patients it doesn't, but in a lot of cases

00:03:22.479 --> 00:03:29.199
it does. So the T cells, once they are supercharged, they are also given instructions to grow. So this

00:03:29.199 --> 00:03:34.479
is very complicated. They've got to find something. They have to attack it, kill it. They also have to

00:03:34.479 --> 00:03:40.960
multiply inside the body after being engineered this way. So where do I come in? I'm a statistician,

00:03:40.960 --> 00:03:45.440
classically trained. So this quality control part is very important. There's a lot of data that's

00:03:45.440 --> 00:03:51.679
collected. There's also this notion in manufacturing of specifications. So a lot of software development

00:03:51.679 --> 00:03:55.919
people in the audience, either like me, an accidental programmer, or you do it really for a

00:03:55.919 --> 00:04:06.960
living, and you're very good at it. But what we're trying to do here is make sure that we have

00:04:06.960 --> 00:04:12.080
specifications when we manufacture a batch from the patient do not go outside of those

00:04:12.080 --> 00:04:17.600
specifications. Those specifications talk about potency. They talk about impurities. There's all

00:04:17.600 --> 00:04:21.119
kinds of things. It's biology. There's all kinds of things that go wrong when we're trying to

00:04:21.119 --> 00:04:27.679
control cells and make them grow and do certain things. Then it goes back into the patient. So

00:04:28.079 --> 00:04:36.959
that's the end of the cycle there. So as a statistician, I have to fit models to data. I have

00:04:36.959 --> 00:04:42.480
to evaluate them. I have to do a lot of intervals that predict what's going to happen to help set

00:04:42.480 --> 00:04:47.040
these specifications, also to make sure when we run out of specification or making changes, we

00:04:47.040 --> 00:04:53.359
don't increase risks and so on. A lot of times, of course, the patients are at the center of

